node.text:
In almost every way measurable, millennials in the U.S. at 40 are doing worse financially than the generations that came before them.

Fewer millennials own homes than their parents did at their age. They have more debt — especially student debt. They simply aren’t as wealthy. 

Now, if predictions of a long, post-Covid economic boom are to be believed, this may be the last opportunity an entire generation has to build wealth before heading off into retirement.

node.title: Millennials Are Running Out of Time to Build Wealth to Retire

node.text:
Taiwan is becoming a bigger issue between the world's two biggest superpowers. Taipei — a U.S. ally — and Beijing have avoided war for more than seven decades, but that balance is getting harder to maintain as China becomes more assertive in its desire for reunification.

Watch the full video at the link in bio to understand why analysts say Taiwan's status is "the most likely issue to draw China and the U.S. into a direct military conflict."

node.title: Why the Biggest U.S.-China Issue Is About Taiwan

node.text:
Across the U.S., hospitals are running out of intensive-care beds.

Delta's march began in the U.S. in the Ozarks and South, in states and regions with low vaccination rates. But the surge has shown that even the best vaccinated areas still don’t have enough immunity against the highly transmissible variant.
 
It’s clear the pandemic isn’t done with America, particularly in places where residents have shunned shots or resisted the renewal of mask mandates and other public-health measures. In a few states, the unvaccinated are entering intensive care at rates matching the winter wave. Tap the link in our bio for state-by-state data.

node.text:
The majority of Morgan Stanley interns in Europe and the U.S. want to work flexibly when they enter the workforce full time, according to a survey.

There's one issue: their boss, CEO James Gorman, wants them back in the office. 

While Gorman said in July the bank "would be flexible where flexibility was called for," he has joined other Wall Street executives in making it clear that he expects his workforce to return — at least, largely — to the office, assuming it is safe to do so.
 
Someone’s going to wind up disappointed. More at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 10, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'OFTHE THE STATE New York Governor Andrew Cuomo OF resigns after harrassment allegations PEO SਬOT Governor Andrew M. Cuomo Bloomberg'.

node.text:
New York Governor Andrew Cuomo announced his resignation on Tuesday, bowing to pressure to leave office or face impeachment.

The move marks a stunning fall for his decades-long political career. For months, Cuomo had dug in, refusing to leave office even after New York Attorney General Letitia James found that he had violated multiple federal and state harassment laws. County prosecutors are weighing criminal charges, while accusers are considering civil lawsuits.

He maintained that he didn’t harass anyone but was “thoughtless” in the way he spoke to and touched women on his staff. Read more at the link in bio.

node.text:
EXCLUSIVE: Apple’s next iPhone lineup will get at least three major new camera and video-recording features: a video version of Portrait mode, the ability to record in a higher-quality format, and a new filters-like system that improves the look and colors of photos. They’ll also include a faster A15 chip and screen technology that could enable a faster refresh rate for smoother scrolling.

The camera features are seen as some of the biggest selling points for the iPhone 12’s successor, which is expected to go on sale in the next several weeks. Find out more at the link in bio.

node.text:
Lionel Messi is traveling to France after agreeing to join Paris Saint-Germain, according to The Associated Press.

The 34-year-old Argentina star is set to agree a two-year deal worth about $41 million a year, a source says, after his contract with his career-long club Barcelona expired.

Funded for a decade by Qatari sovereign wealth, PSG is one of the few clubs in the world that could finance the signing of Messi. Tap the link in our bio for the latest.

node.text:
Researchers have asked U.S. regulators to remove some sunscreens made by Coppertone, Banana Boat and Neutrogena from shelves, the latest in a series of requests from scientists concerned about their ingredients.
 
The move follows research that reported finding cancer-linked chemicals in sunscreen sprays and lotions. J&J and CVS have already recalled or halted sales of products that contained benzene; scientists' attention has now turned to another chemical called benzophenone.
 
An industry group said the research "needlessly misleads and scares consumers." The FDA is reviewing the data. Tap the link in bio for our Q&A.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 09, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, outdoors and text that says 'College grads with excel skills are the hottest thing on Wall Street Bloomberg'.

node.text:
All across Wall Street, one price keeps going up: the one for young talent.

2021 is one of the toughest years for finance recruitment in recent memory. Virtually every major bank has bumped up base pay for entry-level analysts and bankers by roughly 17%, setting a new industry standard of $100,000 — sometimes more, as is the case at Goldman Sachs, which is offering $110,000.

With annual summer internships about to wind down, trading desks and investment banking units are bracing for a sudden shortage of young Excel whizzes to do the donkey work — and for now, at least, the war for talent keeps escalating. Tap the link in bio for more.

node.text:
It would be hard to find someone who lost as much money as quickly as Bill Hwang did in March 2021.

The previously unknown Wall Street whale and his family firm, Archegos Capital, triggered losses of more than $20 billion in just two days. The result was one of the most spectacular implosions in modern financial history. Watch in full, for free, via the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 09, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing and text that says 'China's Covid- strategy couldleaveitisolatedforyears years leave for Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Most of the world is learning to live with Covid-19, but China is tethering itself to eliminating the virus over the long term — an approach that risks leaving the world’s second-biggest economy isolated for years to come.

This month, the delta variant popped up in more than half of 31 provinces despite watertight border controls, triggering yet another round of targeted lockdowns, travel restrictions and mass testing.

The aggressive moves to tame a relatively small caseload (141 as of last Friday, according to the WHO) shows how politically invested the Communist Party has become in achieving zero Covid-19 infections. Chinese authorities are increasingly trumpeting their success in containing the virus as an ideological and moral victory over the U.S. and other nations now treating it as endemic. Find out more at the link in bio.

📷: AFP/Getty Images

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 09, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Delta's spread could spell the end for returning to theoffice the five days a week Bloomberg'.

node.text:
If this week proved anything, it’s that America’s largest companies — on Wall Street, in Silicon Valley and everywhere in between — are struggling to keep their grip on where you need to be to do your job.

Within just the past few days, Amazon delayed its office return by four months — corporate staff won’t head back until January. For BlackRock and Wells Fargo, the delay was a month, from September to October. This comes on the heels of recent postponements at Apple, Lyft and Google. All were responding to the rapid spread of Covid’s delta variant.

“Delta is probably the final nail in the coffin of the five-day return to the office,” says Nick Bloom, an economics professor at Stanford University. Read more at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 09, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, money and text.

node.text:
On a white plastic chair, by a swing set and a freshly mowed lawn, sits former Archegos head Bill Hwang.
 
Few people in suburban Tenafly, about 15 miles from midtown Manhattan, realize his link to one of the biggest debacles in Wall Street. "Billion with a B?" gasps a neighbor down the block. 

Four months after Arechegos rocked global finance, bankers and federal authorities are still sifting through the wreckage. Hwang is searching for answers too. Read the full story via the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 09, 2021. May be an image of fire, outdoors and text that says 'Itis "unequivocal" thathuman activity warmed the planet, major UN report says Bloomberg'.

node.text:
A landmark report from the world’s top climate scientists warns that the planet will warm 1.5° Celsius in the next two decades without drastic moves to eliminate greenhouse gas pollution.

In its first major assessment in nearly a decade, the UN-backed Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change also speaks with unprecedented certainty about humankind’s responsibility for rising temperatures.
 
Among the headline findings: The past decade was most likely hotter than any period in the last 125,000 years, when sea levels were as much as 10 meters higher. Read more via the link in our bio.
